experiences. Largely overlooked, however, are the subtle links between these religious expressions. Based on intensive fieldwork conducted among worshippers in Bengal's Navadvip-Mayapur sacred complex, this book discusses the diverse and contrasting ways in which Bengal-Vaishnava devotees experience sacred geography and divinity. Sukanya Sarbadhikary documents an extensive range of practices, which draw on the interactions of mind, body, and viscera. She shows how perspectives on religion, embodiment, affect, and space are enriched when sacred spatialities of internal and external forms are studied at once.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAnthropology of religionzIndiazBengal. 0aSacred spacezIndiazBengal. 0aVaishnavismzIndiazBengal. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh  abengal religious sites.  abengal vaishnavism.  abengal.  abengali pilgrimages.  abody in place.  acontemporary anthropology of place.  ahindu geography.  ahindu pilgrimage.  ahindu religious practices.  ahinduism.  ahindus.  akrishna.  anavadvip mayapur.  apolitics of space.  apopular hinduism.  areligious practice in bengal.  areligious studies.  asacred geography.  asacred topography.  ashiva.  asociology of religion.  asynaesthesia.  avaishnava ritual.  avaishnavite pilgrimages.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520962668?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520962668zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520962668/